n;they want. Many shoppers will\nnot be able to find some toys\ni they have heard about.\nThe reason: Tight money.\nThe big toy shows are held\nearly In the year. The big\nbuyers, the chains and large\nIndependent est a b lishments.\nlook over the field and begin\nplacing orders. By July, manu\nfacturers have a large part of\ntheir orders booked and have\nTRADE\nW/NDS j\nBy LOl? SCHNEIDER\nA survey was made of\nrespected business analysts.\nTheir opinion Is that though\nthe economy may hold at high\nlevels the otfds favor an easing\nto lower levels rather than a\ni further rise.\nThere Is a possibility the\nfinal quarter of the year will\nsee a gain of three or four\npoints in the Federal Reserve\nindustrial production index\n(now at 143). But it will not\nstimulate much optimism\nThat\u2019s because the consumer!\nbuying attitude now shows\ncaution and price resistance.\nThe magazine Steel believes\nthe general business outlook for\n1957 to be as good as 1956. and\nperhaps slightly better. But it\nnotes an Important difference\nbetween the two years: The\nover-all trend in \u201956 was gen\nerally upward, while the trend\nthis year Is slightly down.\nAll business analysts are\naware the Federal Reserve\nBoard and the Elsenhower ad\nministration are. acting to halt\nthe inflation sweeping the coun\ntry. This means official pres\nsure on spending by corpora\ntions and the Government. The\nimpact will slow down the\nbusiness boom.\nSum-up: This may be an\neconomy of marked stability,\nbut certainly not an economy\nwhere sharp fluctuations will\nbe eliminated. Said a bank\neconomist: This Is the time for\nall good executives to keep a\nclose watch on all conditions\nthat affect their business.\n\nThe cost of living is now at\nan all-time high, with June\nshowing a gain for tenth conse\ncutive month. Bulk of the lat\nest gain was in foodstuffs. Com\nmissioner Ewan Clague thinks.\nJuly will show another increase.'\nbut expects some dip in August\ni and thereafter. Most econom\nists don\u2019t agree, however.\nFarm output is expected to\nshow a 5 per cent decline this\nyear. Weather conditions have\nhurt food crops\u2014vegetables and\nj fruits. Wages are going higher\nAnother freight-rate increase:,\nis imminent. Prices of finished\ngoods for consumers\u2014processed i\nfoods, wearing apparel, house\nhold equipment, etc.\u2014are mov\ning higher. The cost of living:\nwill climb.\n(Consolidated Newafeaturen)\nDIVIDENDS\nNEW YORK, AUf 2 Dividends\nannounced.\nPe- Stic of Pay- 1 1\nRate. rlod. record able\nIrrrffular\ni Puritan Pund He K-l j\nInitial i\nAm Coml Bane L *iftc M-:n\u00bb IM*\u2019\nODD-LOT DEALINGS\nNEW YORK. Aug 2 14': \u2014Thr New\nYork Stock Kxrhange reported today\nthese odd lot tranaactlon.s bv principal\ndealer* on the exchange for Auiuat I:\npurchase of 'JIO.PSI shared sales ol i\nshares including shares\nsold short.\nUNITED STATES TREASURY POSITION\nBy the Associated Press\nThe cash position of the Treasure compared wlih corrrspondlnv date a\nyear ago: July :ln. llsfl* July .111. IW.ltt\nBalance tl,4\u00bb\u00bb,ft.t;i.tJ*A AS I.M'.VJI I.Olltt :I3\nDwjalts Bfalyaar >'*ly 1.._ .ll.M.mi.yvM I\" ;t,4t\u00abi.TPi>.lSH4 02\nWithdrawals Bscal year il.min,;i4:l.H?:i.4il .Y414.4MA.42t Ad\nTotal debt \u2022'!TU.*HT. .174.4112 ?w 2?'.MH.'l.??l.Hta 4d\nGold assets !!S.*t2H.46o,'J*. 41 MW.140.046.07\nliatudes (444.680,061. ff debt not subject to )p.\u00abtutorr limit. i\nNYNHH 4*40 2022 44\nNYNHU 4a 2007 55\nNiagMobP 4Hs 71 103*4\nNor Pac 3s 2047 61H\nPar GAE 4Hx 40 99*4\nPac GAE 3s 71 83\nPac GAE la 74 62*4\nPao TAI 49m H 99\nPeo RR 494\u00a7 00 99H\nPen RR 4tM 05 99\nPbililMPef 414 s 17 10\u00ab*41\nRCA IHs M 94 i\nScott Paolo7l 9414\nSearsAretptlM 71 99\nSinrin*! 44m If 2CBH\nSo ReR TT 2V,\u00ab tS 76\nSo Col Ed 3Hs 70 106*4\nSo Par 4*4a 00 92*4\nStd CoU P 5# 67 77*4\nStd O Ind IHs HI US\nW Shore 4s 2301 60*4\nWis Cen 4s 2004 63*4\nFOREIGN 1:11\nAustral 3%s 60 60\ntulle 1* 93 41\nColom 3e 70 57\nGreek is 69 17*4\nHigh Au