h fewer orders and\nless information about the size\nand preferences of the market.\nThey are sule of demand for\nsome items, such as the old\nstandbys. But they have doubts\nabout the market for newer\nPlaythings.\ni This has clouded manufac\nturing plans. Furthermore, be-i\ncause of ttght-money situation,\nonly the biggest producers of\nsure-fire hits have been able to|\nafford the risk of plunging\nahead.\nOrders, of course, will come\nin from now on. In fact, they\nare expected to reach marks\n5 or 10 per cent above last\nyear. But a lot of manufac\nturing time has been lost.\nPrices Up, Too\nThe industry is so big and\nthere are so many manufac\nturers and items that there will\nbe a choice for Christmas\ngifts. But the special toy that;\nJunior has set his heart on may i\nbe hard to find.\nToys will be a little more ex-'\npensive this year. The cost of\nlabor and materials has risen\nand will be reflected in prices'\nconsumers pay.\nToys will be more realistic\nthis year. Melvin Freud, presi-1\ndent of the Toy Guidance\nCouncil, says that youngsters!\nare continually demanding!\nmore realism and the toy Navy I\nPom Pom guns. Turbojet planes'\nand Nike rocket launchers must\nbe accurate in detail. His\u2019\nstatement has borne out by toys\ndisplayed at the council's July\npress preview of educator\napproved toys.\nj (McClure Newspaper Syndicate)\nFOREIGN EXCH'GE\ntX* S G '\u00a3a7BS\n'.n dollar,, other, in renu, Bm n I\nmark?? '.T, ln ,w \"0*\" 1\n10834% linii'H p 2. r,nt prrm lum or\n!of a cent.\nL ro U ,L op i-P r 9 t Britain (pound).\nI tS 'V o 30-day future,.\nrent: 90-day future,. 2.77 0/32. un!\nrhlSH?' 'franc, 1.99'/,, u?.\nl** n ed (franc i, of g\ncent, unchanged; Qermany <westerni\n'nni\"lf*** uaehStS\nHolland (guilder). off 01%\n,of a cent; Italy <llra>. .10% 0 f a rent\nI P\u00b0 rt ugal (escudo). :i.50! 1\nunchanged. Sweden (Krona). 1H.14\nI li5 c nge{l u \u00dfwlt,frltnd r nc /free)\n..i.M, unchanged. Denmtrk (krone).\n14.00. unchanged\nio \u2014A